<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-144-490  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 144 490.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 27 1989 v6 n12 p84(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DCA stock plunges as weak sales prompt sell recommendation.andO;(Digital Communications Associates)</TITLE><AUTHOR>March, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Communications Associates Inc. (investment activities).andO;Ticker:    DCA.andO;Topic:     Communications IndustryStock MarketInvestmentsWeeklyReportsIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>In the turbulent world of computer stocks, Digital Communications AssociatesInc. is one of the most volatile.andP;  So it was no surprise last week when DCAtook another abrupt turn.andM;Shares of the Alpharetta, Ga., connectivity company tumbled 12.8 percent onMarch 22 after a securities analyst reduced his rating on DCA from a hold toa sell.andP;  The stock fell from 21-1/2 to 18-3/4 points on volume of 491,100shares, more than twice its average daily volume of 196,500 shares.andM;Alex.andP;  Brown andamp; Sons Inc. analyst Douglas Whitman said he lowered his ratingbecause analysts expect sales of DCA's PC-to-mainframe IRMA products, weak inthe second fiscal quarter, to remain soft in the third quarter, which endsthis month.andM;IRMA sales accounted for an estimated 60 percent of fiscal 1988 revenues of$227 million.andP;  Sales of the 6-year-old IRMA products have declined as localarea network solutions gain popularity.andM;Declining sales of IRMA products, whose gross margins are estimated at 80percent, are prompting analysts to lower earnings estimates for the fiscalyear ending in June.andP;  Estimates place per-share earnings at as low as half ofthe 1988 level of $2.77.andM;Rumors of internal troubles have trailed DCA in recent months.andP;  The companysaid last week it had no corporate news to report.andP;  -- Richard March</TEXT></DOC>